:"11 oktober 1688","11 October 1688":"11 oktober 1688","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1577":"1577","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1603":"1603","1625":"1625","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Winslow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Winslow, Buckinghamshire, England"},"en":{"about 2 July 1580–11 October 1688":"about 2 July 1580–11 October 1688","1580–1688":"1580–1688","1577–1625":"1577–1625","1600–1688":"1600–1688","–Male":"Deceased","1565–1603":"1565–1603","about 2 July 1580":"about 2 July 1580","1580":"1580","11 October 1688 ":"11 October 1688","11 October 1688":"11 October 1688","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1577":"1577","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1603":"1603","1625":"1625","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Winslow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Winslow, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Echols","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of English   Eccles   and possibly also of German   Eckels  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eccles","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Eccles in Lancashire, or possibly from any of several other places so named in Kent, Norfolk, Berwickshire, and Dumfriesshire, from British <i>eglēs</i> ‘Romano-British Christian church’ (from Latin <i>ecclesia</i>, Greek <i>ekklēsia</i> ‘gathering, assembly’). Such places would have been the sites of notable pre-Anglo-Saxon churches or Christian places of communal worship."]},{"name":"Echoles","meanings":["Variant of   Echols  ."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Monroe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the Scottish surname, usually spelled <i>Munro</i>. The ancestors of the Scottish Munros are said to have originally come from Ireland, apparently from a settlement by the River Roe in County Derry; their name is therefore supposed to be derived from Gaelic <i>bun Rotha</i> ‘mouth of the Roe’. In the United States the popularity of the given name may have been influenced by the fame of  James Monroe  (  1758–1831 ), fifth president of the United States and propounder (in  1823 ) of the  Monroe Doctrine , asserting that European powers should not seek to colonize in North or South America and that the United States would not intervene in European affairs."],"variants":[{"name":"Munro","meanings":["Transferred use of the Scottish surname, usually spelled <i>Munro</i>. The ancestors of the Scottish Munros are said to have originally come from Ireland, apparently from a settlement by the River Roe in County Derry; their name is therefore supposed to be derived from Gaelic <i>bun Rotha</i> ‘mouth of the Roe’. In the United States the popularity of the given name may have been influenced by the fame of  James Monroe  (  1758–1831 ), fifth president of the United States and propounder (in  1823 ) of the  Monroe Doctrine , asserting that European powers should not seek to colonize in North or South America and that the United States would not intervene in European affairs."]},{"name":"Monro","meanings":["Transferred use of the Scottish surname, usually spelled <i>Munro</i>. The ancestors of the Scottish Munros are said to have originally come from Ireland, apparently from a settlement by the River Roe in County Derry; their name is therefore supposed to be derived from Gaelic <i>bun Rotha</i> ‘mouth of the Roe’. In the United States the popularity of the given name may have been influenced by the fame of  James Monroe  (  1758–1831 ), fifth president of the United States and propounder (in  1823 ) of the  Monroe Doctrine , asserting that European powers should not seek to colonize in North or South America and that the United States would not intervene in European affairs."]},{"name":"Munroe","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Monroe ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":4,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":6,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":39,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705213,"age":61,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705216,"age":107,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"James Monroe Echols was born about 2 July 1580, in Buckinghamshire, England as the son of Echols and Elizabeth M. Palmer. He married Elizabeth Johnston. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 11 October 1688, in his hometown, at the age of 108."},"et":{"about 2 July 1580–11 October 1688":"umbes 2. juuli 1580–11. oktoober 1688","1580–1688":"1580–1688","1577–1625":"1577–1625","1600–1688":"1600–1688","–Male":"Surnud","1565–1603":"1565–1603","about 2 July 1580":"umbes 2. juuli 1580","1580":"1580","11 October 1688 ":"11. oktoober 1688","11 October 1688":"11. oktoober 1688","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1577":"1577","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1603":"1603","1625":"1625","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Winslow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Winslow, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 2 July 1580–11 October 1688":"noin 2. heinäkuuta 1580–11. lokakuuta 1688","1580–1688":"1580–1688","1577–1625":"1577–1625","1600–1688":"1600–1688","–Male":"Kuollut","1565–1603":"1565–1603","about 2 July 1580":"noin 2. heinäkuuta 1580","1580":"1580","11 October 1688 ":"11. lokakuuta 1688","11 October 1688":"11. lokakuuta 1688","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1577":"1577","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1603":"1603","1625":"1625","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Buckingha